{:concepts/version 1
 :concepts/description
 "Concept mappings for protocol-robustness-v0 benchmark.
 
 Each concept maps a robustness dimension to stakeholder-readable
 language, referencing the specific scenario, claim, and evidence
 types that support it.

 CROSS-REFERENCE: The :robustness/evidence-integrity concept used
 by this benchmark is defined in benchmarks/concepts/evidence-integrity-v1.edn
 (the canonical evidence-integrity dimension definition). The concept
 file is maintained independently because both protocol-robustness-v0
 and deterministic-replay-v1 reference the same evidence integrity
 dimension."

 :concepts
 [{:concept/id :robustness/resolver-accountability
   :concept/title "Resolver accountability"
   :concept/summary
   "Whether resolver corruption or bias is economically bounded.
    A corrupt resolver should not profit from a biased verdict."
   :concept/stakeholder-language
   "If the resolver acts dishonestly, the protocol should limit
    their gains and compensate affected parties. Users should not
    bear the full cost of resolver misconduct."
    :concept/maps-to
    {:scenarios ["malicious-resolver-verdict-v1"]
     :claims    [:evidence-root-present :replay-result-present]
     :invariants ["slashable-liability-preserved"]
     :evidence  [:evidence/dispute-decision :evidence/economic-transfer]}
   :concept/why-it-matters
   "Resolver accountability is the primary safeguard against
    capture. Without economic bounds, a resolver can extract value
    at will, making escrow meaningless."}

  {:concept/id :robustness/liveness-under-load
   :concept/title "Liveness under adversarial load"
   :concept/summary
   "Whether the protocol makes timely progress even when a
    malicious party floods the dispute queue."
   :concept/stakeholder-language
   "A malicious party should not be able to freeze the protocol by
    filing excessive disputes. Honest users should still get timely
    resolutions."
    :concept/maps-to
    {:scenarios ["dispute-flooding-v1"]
     :claims    [:evidence-root-present :replay-result-present]
     :invariants ["bounded-progress-under-load"]
     :evidence  [:evidence/dispute-count :evidence/timing]}
   :concept/why-it-matters
   "Liveness failures are invisible to casual observers but can
    lock user funds indefinitely. This is the most practical
    denial-of-service vector for escrow protocols."}

  {:concept/id :robustness/escrow-fund-safety
   :concept/title "Escrow fund safety"
   :concept/summary
   "Whether escrowed funds can only move through intended pull
    paths, preventing unsafe external pushes or settlement
    bypasses."
   :concept/stakeholder-language
   "Funds should only leave escrow when the intended recipient
    pulls them. No external actor should be able to push funds out
    without proper authorization."
    :concept/maps-to
    {:scenarios ["autopush-settlement-v1"]
     :claims    [:evidence-root-present :replay-result-present]
     :invariants ["pull-first-value-flow"]
     :evidence  [:evidence/settlement-path :evidence/value-transfer]}
   :concept/why-it-matters
   "Pull-first settlement is a fundamental safety pattern. Without
    it, a compromised resolver or governance action could drain
    escrows in a single transaction."}

   ]}
